#let images = (
  "18.1": (
    caption: [Simplified diagram of a primary root showing the root cap, meristematic zone, elongation zone, and maturation zone. The root apical meristem (RAM) contains undifferentiated cells that continuously divide to produce new cells for root growth. The root cap protects the delicate meristem as the root pushes through soil.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.2": (
    caption: [All the tissues in the Arabidopsis root are derived from a small number of initial cells in the root apical meristem. (A) Longitudinal section through the center of a root showing the meristem containing the initials that give rise to all tissues. (B) Diagram showing the position of initial cells and the tissues they produce, including epidermis, cortex, endodermis, pericycle, and vascular tissues.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.3": (
    caption: [Auxin and cytokinin gradients combined with PLETHORA expression influence the position of the transition between the meristematic zone and the elongation zone. An auxin maximum coinciding with cytokinin and WOX5 near the meristematic initials enhances the abundance of PLETHORA transcription factors, which maintain meristematic identity. As cells move away from this zone, declining PLETHORA levels promote the transition to cell elongation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.4": (
    caption: [Shoot apex of a tomato plant. This scanning electron micrograph shows the basic features of the shoot apex, including a central dome-shaped region which maintains uncommitted initials, and a series of leaf primordia (P1, P2, P3) which have successively emerged at lateral positions on the flanks of the shoot apex. The leaf primordia enclose and protect the delicate shoot apical meristem.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.5": (
    caption: [The Arabidopsis shoot apical meristem can be analyzed in terms of cytological zones or cell layers. (A) The shoot apical meristem has cytological zones including the central zone (CZ) containing slowly dividing stem cells, the peripheral zone (PZ) where leaf primordia initiate, and the rib meristem (RM) that contributes to stem growth. (B) The shoot apical meristem is organized into distinct cell layers: L1 (epidermal layer), L2, and L3, each with specific clonal contributions to different tissues.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.6": (
    caption: [Model of the feedback loop that maintains initial cells in the shoot apical meristem (SAM). The CLAVATA-WUSCHEL (CLV-WUS) feedback loop regulates stem cell maintenance: WUS promotes stem cell identity in the central zone, while CLV signaling restricts WUS expression to prevent excessive stem cell accumulation, ensuring a stable meristem size.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.7": (
    caption: [Model for how expression of the KNOX transcription factor STM elevates cytokinin concentrations while repressing gibberellin (GA) in the shoot apical meristem. P4 is a developing leaf, and P0 is the site where the next leaf primordium will form. KNOX genes maintain meristematic identity by promoting cytokinin biosynthesis and inhibiting GA accumulation, preventing premature differentiation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.8": (
    caption: [Three types of leaf arrangements (phyllotactic patterns) along the shoot axis: alternate (spiral), opposite (decussate), and whorled. These patterns reflect the geometric positioning of leaf primordia initiation at the shoot apical meristem and are determined by auxin distribution patterns. The same terms are also used for inflorescences and flowers.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.9": (
    caption: [Local auxin maxima determine the position of leaf primordia. (A) Sites of leaf formation are related to patterns of polar auxin transport. Patterns of auxin movement (arrows) can be inferred from asymmetric localization of PIN proteins. P0, P1, P2, and P3 refer to the ages of leaf primordia; P0 corresponds to the site where the next primordium will form. (B) Computer simulation showing elimination of leaf primordia when auxin transport is disrupted. (C) In tomato, PIN1 protein localization (shown in green) correlates with sites of auxin accumulation and leaf initiation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.10": (
    caption: [The tomato mutant lateral suppressor (ls) shows defects in axillary bud formation. (A) Wild-type tomato with normal axillary buds in leaf axils. (B) The ls mutant, in which axillary buds fail to form in most of the leaf axils, resulting in reduced branching. This demonstrates the importance of LATERAL SUPPRESSOR transcription factor in initiating axillary meristems.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.11": (
    caption: [Accumulation of LATERAL SUPPRESSOR mRNA as indicated by in situ hybridization in the axillary bud regions of an Arabidopsis shoot tip. P1–P4 are leaf primordia. The expression pattern shows that LAS is specifically expressed in the boundary region between the stem and leaf primordia, where new axillary meristems develop, indicating its role in axillary meristem initiation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.12": (
    caption: [Overview of leaf structure. (A) Shoot structure showing three types of leaf polarity: adaxial–abaxial (upper–lower surface), distal–proximal (tip–base), and midrib–margin (center–edge). (B) Examples of simple leaves showing variations in lower leaf structure including the presence or absence of stipules and petioles, and leaf sheaths. (C) Examples of compound leaves showing different degrees of leaflet division.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.13": (
    caption: [Growth patterns determine organ shape. (A) Isotropic growth increases size with no change in shape, whereas anisotropic growth increases one axis preferentially. Here, both final shapes have doubled in area. (B) Computational model of Arabidopsis leaf development, color-coded to represent growth rate (red fast, green slow) and with arrows representing principal orientations of growth. Different growth patterns along different axes produce diverse leaf shapes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.14": (
    caption: [Diagram of microsurgical technique used in early experiments in potato (Solanum tuberosum) to determine the influence of the shoot apical meristem on leaf primordium (P) development. (A) A primordium initial (I) isolated from the SAM by a transverse incision subsequently grows radially and contains only abaxial tissues. (B) A primordium initial (I) that is only partially isolated from the SAM subsequently shows normal adaxial–abaxial polarity, demonstrating that signals from the SAM are required for establishing adaxial leaf identity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.15": (
    caption: [Effects of phan mutations on leaf morphology in Antirrhinum majus. (A) The vegetative shoot of a wild-type plant with normal leaves showing proper adaxial–abaxial polarity. (B) The vegetative shoot of a phan mutant shows altered adaxial–abaxial symmetry, with narrow (n), needlelike (n-l), and mosaic (m) leaves. PHAN encodes a MYB transcription factor required for adaxial leaf development.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.16": (
    caption: [A network of transcription factors regulates leaf polarity. (A) Regulation of proximal–distal polarity showing various genes involved in proximal–distal patterning that interact with specific genes in the adaxial–abaxial gene network. (B) Gene networks involved in leaf margin growth and adaxial–abaxial polarity. HD-ZIP III genes specify adaxial identity, KANADI and YABBY genes specify abaxial identity, and WOX genes promote margin outgrowth by repressing both adaxial and abaxial programs.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.17": (
    caption: [Scanning electron micrograph of tomato shoot tip showing developing compound leaf. Primordia 1 through 4 (P1–P4) are shown. The first primary leaflet pair (PL) and the second leaflet pair (arrow) are visible on P4. This demonstrates how compound leaves form by redeploying gene regulatory networks used during initial leaf primordium formation to create leaflet primordia.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.18": (
    caption: [Development of compound leaves. The initial stages of simple and compound leaf development are similar. KNOX1 genes are repressed in the primordium initial (1) and are subsequently reactivated (2), thereby maintaining the primordium in an undifferentiated state. Leaflet primordia are then initiated in a process resembling the initiation of leaf primordia involving PIN1-mediated auxin flow (3 and 4). In simple leaves, KNOX1 genes remain repressed, allowing the entire primordium to differentiate as a single blade.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.19": (
    caption: [Stomatal development mutants. (A) Wild-type Arabidopsis showing normal stomatal distribution. (B) Wild-type grass leaf showing normal stomatal pattern. (C) spch mutant in which no cells enter the stomatal lineage, resulting in no stomata. (D) mute mutant in which amplifying cell divisions occur but no mature stomata form. (E) fama mutant in which clusters of unpaired guard cells are visible. (F) scrm mutant in which all the cells become guard cells.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.20": (
    caption: [Stomatal development in Arabidopsis showing the progression from meristemoid mother cell (MMC) to guard cell formation. The process involves asymmetric cell divisions, amplifying divisions of meristemoids, formation of guard mother cells (GMC), and finally symmetric division to produce guard cells. The spacing pathway ensures proper stomatal distribution and prevents stomatal clusters.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.21": (
    caption: [Polarized cell division and peptide signaling regulate stomatal spacing. Three related transcription factors—SPCH, MUTE, and FAMA—form heterodimers with SCRM and are required for the production of meristemoids, GMCs, and guard cells. (A) EPF2 and EPF1 peptides negatively regulate stomatal density and patterning. EPF2 is synthesized and secreted by meristemoid mother cells and early meristemoids to inhibit adjacent cells from becoming stomatal lineage cells. (B) These peptides are perceived by receptor complexes that activate MAPK cascades, leading to phosphorylation and inactivation of SPCH, MUTE, or FAMA, thereby controlling stomatal spacing and preventing clusters.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.22": (
    caption: [Stomatal development in grasses involves orthologs of many of the genes involved in stomatal development in eudicots. However, the roles are different. SCRM and SPCH specify the early asymmetric division. The cells then progress to become guard mother cells and finally stomata without amplifying divisions. Instead, a polarized asymmetric division creates subsidiary cells that surround the stomata, resulting in the characteristic dumbbell-shaped guard cells of grasses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.23": (
    caption: [Two basic patterns of leaf venation in angiosperms. (A) Reticulate (netlike) venation in Prunus serotina, a eudicot, showing an interconnected network of veins with a prominent midvein and branching secondary veins. (B) Parallel venation in Iris sibirica, a monocot, showing longitudinal veins running parallel to each other along the length of the leaf with minimal cross-connections.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.24": (
    caption: [Hierarchy of venation in the mature Arabidopsis leaf based on the diameter of the veins at the site of attachment to the parent vein. The vascular network shows a clear hierarchy from primary (midvein) to secondary, tertiary, and quaternary veins, with freely ending veinlets serving as the smallest units of the vascular network that deliver water and nutrients throughout the leaf blade.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.25": (
    caption: [Early vascular development in a shoot with decussate phyllotaxy. The SAM and a young leaf primordium are indicated in green with procambial strands of a leaf trace extending from this primordium in orange. Leaf traces develop basipetally (toward the base) toward the mature vascular system and join to form a sympodium. Numbers correspond to the leaf order, starting with the primordia, demonstrating the continuous connection between leaf vasculature and stem vasculature.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.26": (
    caption: [Auxin-induced xylem regeneration around a wound in cucumber (Cucumis sativus) stem tissue. (A) Method for carrying out the wound regeneration experiment where a section of stem is removed and auxin is applied. (B) Fluorescence micrograph showing regenerating vascular tissue around the wound. The arrow indicates the wound site where auxin accumulates and xylem differentiation begins, demonstrating that auxin can induce vascular tissue formation and regeneration.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.27": (
    caption: [PIN1-mediated auxin flow during midvein formation. (A) Longitudinal section through a tomato vegetative meristem expressing AtPIN1:GFP (green). The red arrows on the left indicate the direction of auxin movement toward the site of the leaf primordium initial (P0, white asterisk). The red arrows on the right indicate auxin flow toward the emerging leaf primordium (P1). The white arrows show basipetal auxin flow through the developing midvein, demonstrating that PIN1 polarization creates auxin flow patterns that establish the primary vein.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.28": (
    caption: [Preexisting vascular bundle guides basipetal development of the leaf trace. (A and B) In the control Arabidopsis meristem expressing AtPIN1:GFP (green), the newly initiated P0 leaf trace grows toward and connects to the P3 leaf trace directly below it. (C and D) When the P3 vasculature is surgically removed (dashed red line), the P0 leaf trace connects instead to the P2 leaf trace on the other side, demonstrating that developing leaf traces are guided by preexisting vascular patterns.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.29": (
    caption: [Patterning of leaf vein formation. (A) Formation of procambium cells from a pre-procambium cell. When a pre-procambium cell divides, either both daughter cells can become procambium cells or one cell can retain pre-procambium identity. (B) Development of vein pattern in young leaves showing progressive vein formation from midvein to higher-order veins. (C) Radial vein pattern in leaves showing procambial strand, normal vein pattern, and altered vein patterns demonstrating the role of auxin canalization in vein patterning.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.30": (
    caption: [Auxin biosynthesis at the hydathodes of Arabidopsis leaves, as indicated by the expression of the GUS reporter gene driven by the auxin-responsive DR5 promoter. (A) An Arabidopsis leaf that has been cleared to reveal the blue stain showing auxin accumulation at leaf margins and vein tips. (B) Auxin flow and canalization from the hydathode toward a developing leaf vein, demonstrating that auxin produced at the leaf margin serves as a source for vein formation through canalization.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "18.31": (
    caption: [Mutations that affect auxin transport or auxin biosynthesis alter leaf venation patterns in young Arabidopsis rosette leaves. (A) Wild-type leaf with normal reticulate venation. (B) yuc1/yuc2/yuc4/yuc6 quadruple mutant showing that in the absence of significant auxin biosynthesis, the venation pattern is highly reduced. (C) Wild-type leaf treated with the auxin efflux inhibitor NPA, which inhibits both PIN and ABCB efflux activity, showing reduced venation complexity. These results demonstrate the critical role of auxin biosynthesis and transport in establishing leaf vein patterns.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
)
